  "prompt": "Why is coal not considered a mineral?",
  "response": "Coal is not considered a mineral because it does not meet the criteria of a mineral as defined by geologists. A mineral is typically defined as a naturally occurring, inorganic, crystalline solid with a specific chemical composition and a defined crystal structure. Coal, on the other hand, is an organic sedimentary rock formed from the remains of plant material that has been compressed and altered over millions of years. While it is naturally occurring and a solid, coal lacks a crystalline structure and its chemical composition can vary. Therefore, coal is classified as a rock rather than a mineral.",
